Obecnie ja traktuję stres jako po prostu...

A teraz robię je tylko na zawodach.

Tak naprawdę im dłużej żyję, tym bardziej się przekonuję o słuszności tego stwierdzenia.

takie cele, które co jakiś odcinek czasu jesteśmy w stanie odfajkować.
Powiedzieć sobie, o, tą pracę, którą wykonaliśmy, zakończyła się sukcesem.
To jest bardzo ważne dla naszego zdrowia psychicznego, a przede wszystkim dodaje to pewności siebie i wzmacnia naszą motywację.
Równie ważnym odkryciem było w ostatnich latach, gdy spojrzałem w lustro i powiedziałem sobie, że każdy z nas posiada coś takiego, co się nazywa ego.
Może nie wiecie, ale nasz mózg działa w ten sposób, że on za wszelką cenę będzie chronił to ego.

Ale w danym momencie nasz umysł ma zakończenie i my możemy szczęśliwie żyć dalej.
I tutaj docieramy do piękna freedivingu.
Często właśnie nurkując przychodzą mi różne myśli do głowy.
No i jak nurkuję, muszę sobie z tymi myślami poradzić.

Na przykład po ciężkim dniu w pracy przechodzę na basen, zanurzam się pod wodę i wszystkie problemy znikają.
Podsumowując, freediving jest dla mnie niekończącą się podróżą, odkrywaniem własnych słabości i pokonywaniem ich.
Często jestem pytany o to, Jak myślę, gdzie leżą granice ludzkich możliwości?
Gdzie jest ten rekord, który już nie zostanie pobity?
Ciężko odpowiedzieć na to pytanie.

Osobiście ja uważam, że tak długo jak będziemy przede wszystkim zdrowi, tak długo jak będziemy zmotywowani, zainspirowani, będziemy wyszukiwać nowych metod treningowych, będziemy naprawdę wkładali całe swoje serce w to, co robimy, tak długo będziemy się w stanie poprawiać.

Wiecie, ile razy tak myślałem?
I prędzej czy później docierałem do tej granicy i ona się przesuwała.
Limity są tylko w naszych głowach.
Na zakończenie chciałbym jeszcze raz przypomnieć, że freediving jest sportem partnerskim, gdzie po prostu się nurkuje we dwójkę i wtedy jest bardzo bezpieczny.
Nigdy nie nurkujcie sami.
Dziękuję za uwagę.

en.text: Hi, my name is Mateusz Malina.
I am a multiple world champion and record holder in freediving.
Today I would like to tell you how freediving helps me to control my emotions.
I will add that I held my breath for 10 minutes and 4 seconds the longest.
I swam 300 meters underwater, which is 6 Olympic pools, and I dived the deepest for 114 meters.
Today, however, I would like to focus on something else, not on numbers, numbers, records, because it is boring and it changes all the time.
I would like to tell you how freediving helps me in almost every aspect of my life.
In a moment you will hear the sound of my heart beating from the speakers and you will be able to monitor it on the application on the screen.
My normal heart rate is about 40-45 beats per minute.
For an average person who doesn't train any sports, this heart rate is about 60-70 beats per minute.
I'm sure that now this heart rate is 2 or even 3 times higher than mine.
It happens because of stress.
The more stress there is, the higher the heart rate.
Practically, if each of you were in my place, if we were to switch, you would be more or less stressed.
I'm not talking about dictation, about the way you look at things.
I'm talking about the physiological reactions.
What's happening inside and what's not visible.
Why does it happen?
The culprit is the almond body.
The almond body is in our brain and its only task is to protect us at all costs. It's an instinct.
The almond body is twice as fast in making decisions than our rational thoughts.
It means that it works instinctively.
It evolved during many years of evolution and protected our ancestors from predators.
It was just a survival instinct.
Now I would like to move on to the experiment and show you an imitation of my water training.
I can't take you to the pool, not to the sea, not to the lake, I brought a piece of water here.
I have a bowl with cold tap water and I also have an oximeter that I connect to my phone.
You will soon be able to hear the beat of my heart from the speakers.
The upper value, 97, will fluctuate between 97 and 100, if the signal is good.
This is my saturation.
This is the percentage value and it tells me how much oxygen is in my body.
The maximum is 100%.
The lower value is the pulse.
And now it's 90.
So my heart beats 88 times per minute.
That means I'm a bit stressed.
In a moment, I'll hold my breath and I'd like you to pay attention to what happens to the rhythm of my heart beating.
A disclaimer.
Don't try this at home.
Because freediving is just something you have to do for security.
And that's all.
Okay, let's start.
Beeping I'd just like to say that it doesn't hurt me in any way.
As you probably noticed, the upper saturation value, I suspect it didn't drop below 90, but maybe it was still around 100.
This means that I had oxygen in my blood all the time, and I held my breath, but not my circulation.
My circulation is constantly spinning, so my brain is constantly supplied with oxygen.
OK, back to the presentation.
You probably noticed that my whole body relaxed.
The rhythm of my heart beat slowed down.
You didn't see it, but I can tell you that all my thoughts disappeared.
And that's why I didn't want to talk about results and records today, because it doesn't matter if I held my breath for a minute, two, five or ten.
Each of you can feel it, there is no trap from which we can feel it.
Results change all the time.
They were, are and will be.
This is what media are interested in. It's a food for the media.
But that's not why freediving is beautiful. It's a kind of meditation and it's a very spiritual experience, during which we often look deep into ourselves.
When I dive, I have a lot of thoughts in my head.
I have to deal with them.
It's a fight against my own emotions.
I once dived in the Polish Lake Hańcza in 2013.
I was 90 meters deep.
For those who don't know, In Polish lakes, it's usually 10-20 meters deep, but here it's pitch black.
You can't see the tip of your nose.
Someone asked me, Mateusz, what did you see there?
I laughed and said, I didn't see anything.
Because I had my eyes closed all the time.
My eyes were hands on the line that pulled up and down.
You don't even realize how in a state of silence, when we have our eyes closed, how much our senses are sharpening.
In addition, from about 20 meters, my body becomes heavier than water.
This means that without making any movements, I fall. It's very similar to flying. It's called freefall.
It's the most beautiful thing in freediving.
Practically every freediver dreams of being in this freefall as often as possible.
This reminds me of my dive in Egypt in 2010.
My first dive for a magical 100 meters.
During this fall, I imagined I am a cosmonaut who is flying in space, wearing this whole suit and drifting around the orbit, with a beautiful view of the Earth.
As you can guess, nitrogen poisoning had something to do with it.
Nitrogen poisoning is a state For those who don't know, I'll try to explain it, to compare it, to use analogies.
It's a state of light alcohol intoxication, in which you have control over what you do, or at least you think so.
You're happy, but you couldn't drive a car.
You're probably wondering how long such diving takes.
Well, 100 meters is about 3.5 minutes.
Interestingly, I think it takes 30-40 seconds.
It's possible because I repeated such divings, dozens and sometimes hundreds of times during training. It's not about the same depth, it's about the sequence of movements, the whole process.
So I can do it automatically.
And if I do it automatically, there is a certain area where I have more space, so I enter a flow state.
The state of flow is not fully explained by today's scientists.
It is known that the greatest writers, artists, sportsmen, scientists, they create their greatest works in the state of flow.
The state of flow is a state in which our rational mind is turned off and then we let ourselves be carried away by our body, our emotions and we create beautiful things.
And that's what fascinates me the most about freediving.
I trained various sports, netball, judo, swimming, and in each of them, adrenaline helped me.
And freediving was the first sport that bothered me.
At least that was the case at the beginning.
Of course, now all my best dives, both in terms of results and feelings, But I did it in big competitions where there is adrenaline.
How is it possible?
At the beginning, I will use a simple analogy before I come to my example.
Let's assume that there are two men with almost identical physical parameters.
One is running away from the other.
How do you think who will be faster?
It's hard to say.
So now let's set the atmosphere and say that the first one is fighting for his life by running away.
He will be affected by adrenaline and he will definitely be faster.
So, going back to my example, such long diving is possible thanks to diving reflexes.
You've seen one of them in action. It's a rapid slowdown of the heart rate after immersing the face in water and holding your breath.
Even if there wasn't water, my heart rate wouldn't drop so much, but water helps.
The effect is even more intense in motion.
For example, if I was cycling stationary, with medium load, my heart would beat about 100 times per minute.
If I suddenly stopped breathing, after 45 seconds, the rhythm of my heart beating drops to 20-80%.
The effect is even more intense when diving.
At depths of about 100 meters, the heart beats less than 10 beats per minute.
It's one heart beat every 6 seconds or less.
Blood flows from my limbs and gathers in my chest.
For two reasons.
It will supply my brain, heart and most important organs with additional oxygen and protect my chest against contraction.
These effects are called vasoconstriction and centralization of circulation.
The body takes care that the most important organs have oxygen because my muscles don't need it.
They will become acidified and create energy without oxygen.
Probably, the dive rites were formed during evolution and were supposed to increase our chances of survival in a situation when we can't breathe.
Interestingly, among the Saks, the strongest dive rites are among the newborns.
Because they are supposed to protect them from low oxygen levels, to protect the brain from low oxygen levels during birth.
Now I can fully explain how emotions and adrenaline connect with diving reflex.
In every sport, the most beautiful moments come when emotions reach zenith.
The footballer scores an unbelievable goal at the end of the match.
The basketball player scores three points in the NBA final.
When emotions reach zenith.
It's the same with diving reflexes.
Emotions and adrenaline strengthen them.
And if they are stronger, it means that my body has more oxygen.
And that means that it will last longer.
And here we come to stress.
Since I was a child, I was told that stress is bad, it demobilizes us, it is harmful, it lowers our abilities, etc.
This is not true.
It took me a while to realize this, I don't treat stress as something bad.
I just treat it as stress and it helps me.
It helps me in my daily life, to work at higher speed, to be a better self.
And now, for example, in training, I'm not able to achieve my best results.
Because there is no stress. It's like in competition, where there is emotion, adrenaline, pressure.
Of course, it wasn't always like that.
When I started doing freediving, At the beginning, I had great results in training, but not so good in competitions.
So I only did my results in my comfort zone.
After a few years, I started to repeat my results from training to competitions.
And now I do them only in competitions.
Everything happened in my head.
In fact, the longer I live, the more I am convinced of the validity of this statement.
It is very important to set rational goals.
goals that we can achieve in a short period of time.
We can say, this work we've done has been a success.
This is very important for our mental health, and above all, it gives us confidence and strengthens our motivation.
In recent years, I've noticed that everyone has something called ego.
Maybe you don't know, but our brain works in such a way that it will protect our ego at all costs.
It will rationalize every situation so that our ego is calm.
An example.
Many years ago, when I was at competitions, my heart was beating at a speed of 90-120.
My legs were like cotton wool.
The weather forecaster said that tomorrow the pressure will be low, so I was feeling bad.
So I thought, that's why I'm not feeling so good.
I think I could have prepared better.
I could have done something.
I'll swim to swim.
And I'll come back home, I'll train a bit more and in a year, or half a year, or in the next competition, I'll show what I'm capable of. And now I don't have to worry about it.
You see what happened here?
I was able to lose competitions before the competition.
It doesn't matter that in the eyes of others I achieved a good result, but it was It was a fight, and as I said, the results are not important.
Inside, it was a fight and it wasn't pleasant.
I started to enjoy it only when I started to accept it and I started to be well prepared for these negative emotions.
I'm sure many of you have experienced it.
Maybe you know about it or not.
For example, I want to change my shape and I go to the gym, to the diet, etc. The point is that our mind just needs endings.
If we think that we will change it in a week or a month, we won't do it.
But at a certain moment our mind has an end and we can live happily ever after. And here we come to the beauty of freediving.
Often while diving,
I get different thoughts in my head. And when I dive, I have to deal with these thoughts.
And as I dive more often, these thoughts, which I like to call distractions, appear less and less.
For example, after a hard day at work, I go to the pool, I dive under water and all the problems disappear.
To sum up, freediving is an endless journey for me, discovering my own weaknesses and overcoming them.
I am often asked What do I think?
Where are the limits of human possibilities?
Where is the record that will not be broken? It's hard to answer this question.

Personally, I think that as long as we are healthy, as long as we are motivated, inspired, we will look for new training methods, we will really put our hearts into what we do, we will be able to improve in a long time.
How many times have I thought I don't think about results, I don't think that I want to achieve a result.
But sometimes I think, I will never do this.
Do you know how many times I thought like that?
And sooner or later I reached the limit and it shifted.
Limits are only in our heads.
Finally, I would like to remind you once again that freediving is a partner sport.
You just dive in pairs and then it's very safe.
Never dive alone.
Thank you for your attention.
